* GM1 gangliosidosis, caused by a deficiency of the enzyme beta-galactosidase type A (BGA);
* GM2 gangliosidosis, caused by a deficiency of the enzyme beta-galactosidase type B (BGB);
* GM3 gangliosidosis, caused by a deficiency of the enzyme beta-galactosidase type C (BGC);
* GM6 gangliosidosis, caused by a deficiency of the enzyme beta-galactosidase type E (BGE);
* GM7 gangliosidosis, caused by a deficiency of the enzyme beta-galactosidase type F (BGF).
Each of these types of GM1 gangliosidoses has a slightly different set of symptoms and progression, but all are characterized by progressive nerve damage and degeneration. Treatment for GM1 gangliosidoses typically involves a combination of enzyme replacement therapy and other supportive measures, such as physical therapy and speech therapy.
